517
00:37:43,510 --> 00:37:45,366
to cut through the blubber
on them fingers.

518
00:37:45,380 --> 00:37:46,846
Would you not want him
to have to do the one finger

519
00:37:46,860 --> 00:37:48,080
to see if he was bluffing, like?

520
00:37:48,250 --> 00:37:49,250
No, we wouldn't.

521
00:37:49,430 --> 00:37:50,860
That's what I'd have him do,

522
00:37:51,040 --> 00:37:53,033
I'd have him do the one finger
to see if he was bluffin'.

523
00:37:53,040 --> 00:37:54,650
'Cause worst comes to worst,

524
00:37:54,820 --> 00:37:56,606
he can still play the fiddle with
four fingers, I'll bet ya.

525
00:37:56,650 --> 00:37:57,870
Or the banjo.

526
00:37:58,180 --> 00:37:59,346
We don't want any of that.

527
00:37:59,350 --> 00:38:00,806
We just want nothing
to do with him no more.

528
00:38:00,830 --> 00:38:02,480
You don't. This gom does.

529
00:38:03,530 --> 00:38:04,880
I am a gom, is right.

530
00:38:05,050 --> 00:38:06,790
You're not a gom!

531
00:38:08,450 --> 00:38:09,930
Jeez.

532
00:38:10,100 --> 00:38:11,890
This is a depressing house.

533
00:38:12,190 --> 00:38:14,240
Would you prefer your own, so?

534
00:38:14,410 --> 00:38:16,580
I've heard it's a barrel of fecking laughs.

535
00:38:16,630 --> 00:38:18,330
Well, touche.

536
00:38:19,200 --> 00:38:20,550
Too what?

537
00:38:20,720 --> 00:38:22,720
Che. Touche.
It's from the French.

538
00:38:35,910 --> 00:38:38,946
And how is it, Siobhan,
that you was never married?

539
00:38:42,390 --> 00:38:43,753
It's none of your fecking business

540
00:38:43,790 --> 00:38:45,530
how I was never fecking married.

541
00:38:45,700 --> 00:38:46,480
How isn't it?

542
00:38:47,620 --> 00:38:48,570
How isn't it?

543
00:38:49,660 --> 00:38:51,413
Was you never wild?

544
00:38:51,710 --> 00:38:55,280
Wild? Was I never wild?

545
00:38:55,450 --> 00:38:57,100
I don't know what
you're talkin' about, Dominic.

546
00:38:57,280 --> 00:38:59,410
Wild, how? Angry?

547
00:38:59,580 --> 00:39:01,240
'Cause I'm gettin' angry now,
I can tell ya!

548
00:39:01,410 --> 00:39:02,810
Not angry. Wild.

549
00:39:02,980 --> 00:39:04,550
You just keep sayin' wild, Dominic!

550
00:39:04,720 --> 00:39:06,160
Wild!My brother told you, didn't he?

551
00:39:06,330 --> 00:39:07,533
That you'd be out in the road

552
00:39:07,590 --> 00:39:09,330
if you started talking stupid to me?

553
00:39:09,510 --> 00:39:11,420
He said creepy, not stupid.

554
00:39:11,460 --> 00:39:12,666
Well, you've failed
on both counts, haven't ya?

555
00:39:12,730 --> 00:39:13,730
I have.

556
00:39:16,293 --> 00:39:18,540
I'm off to bed and he's not stayin'
here another night, Padraic.

557
00:39:18,560 --> 00:39:20,280
I don't care how depressed you are.

558
00:39:20,300 --> 00:39:21,740
I'd rather have the donkey in.

559
00:39:27,260 --> 00:39:29,180
Foiled again.

560
00:39:29,350 --> 00:39:30,960
But "faint heart" and all that.

561
00:39:39,710 --> 00:39:40,710
Here.

562
00:39:42,450 --> 00:39:44,890
Ye two, ye'll be all right.

563
00:39:46,940 --> 00:39:47,720
Will we be?

564
00:40:37,233 --> 00:40:39,106
Hello there, Mrs. O'Riordan,
I've the milk outside for ya.

565
00:40:39,120 --> 00:40:40,886
So, it's the two weeks
you owe me for now, I think.

566
00:40:40,900 --> 00:40:42,600
Nobody has a lick of news

567
00:40:42,770 --> 00:40:44,950
for us from your side
of the island, Padraic.

568
00:40:45,130 --> 00:40:46,500
Are you going to be the same as them?

569
00:40:46,520 --> 00:40:47,860
I am, Mrs. O'Riordan, I'm afraid.

570
00:40:47,870 --> 00:40:49,610
And I'm in a bit of a rush, so...

571
00:40:49,780 --> 00:40:52,780
Eileen Coughlan had no news.

572
00:40:52,960 --> 00:40:55,570
Vincent Shaughnessy had no news.

573
00:40:55,740 --> 00:40:58,026
It was a poor old week for news.
But then it is, sometimes.

574
00:40:58,050 --> 00:41:00,790
ColmSonnyLarry, he had no news.

575
00:41:00,970 --> 00:41:02,450
Did he not?

576
00:41:02,620 --> 00:41:04,320
That man never talks.

577
00:41:04,490 --> 00:41:06,360
Eh, he talks sometimes.Up himself.

578
00:41:06,440 --> 00:41:08,986
Aye, aye, anyways, so, it's the two weeks
you owe me for now, Mrs. O'Riordan.

579
00:41:09,020 --> 00:41:10,060
As I was sayin'.

580
00:41:14,720 --> 00:41:15,940
Ladies.

581
00:41:16,110 --> 00:41:17,030
Oh, it's Peadar.

582
00:41:17,200 --> 00:41:19,590
Peadar always has a rake of news.

583
00:41:19,770 --> 00:41:22,030
What news have you, Peadar?PEADAR: News, is it?

584
00:41:22,210 --> 00:41:24,770
Fella killed himself, over Rosmuck way.

585
00:41:24,950 --> 00:41:26,690
Walked into a lake for himself.

586
00:41:26,860 --> 00:41:29,300
Twenty-nine and nothing wrong
with him, the fool.

587
00:41:29,470 --> 00:41:30,950
God love us!

588
00:41:31,130 --> 00:41:33,090
No, not "God love us." Fool!

589
00:41:33,390 --> 00:41:34,390
Another fella,

590
00:41:34,570 --> 00:41:36,000
Protestant, of course,

591
00:41:36,180 --> 00:41:38,270
stabbed his missus in Letterkenny.

592
00:41:38,440 --> 00:41:40,180
Six times he stabbed her.

593
00:41:40,350 --> 00:41:42,620
Good God!
And did she die, Peadar?

594
00:41:42,790 --> 00:41:44,400
She did die, aye.

595
00:41:44,710 --> 00:41:46,460
It wasn't with a spoon
he was stabbin' her.

596
00:41:46,490 --> 00:41:47,930
That's a lot of news.

597
00:41:48,100 --> 00:41:51,450
This man has no news,
don't ya not? No-Newsy!

598
00:41:53,060 --> 00:41:54,913
Stukes never have news.MRS. O'RIORDAN: Stukes!

599
00:41:54,930 --> 00:41:56,370
Funny.

600
00:41:56,670 --> 00:41:59,420
There was a bit of news
I remembered, Mrs. O'Riordan.

601
00:41:59,590 --> 00:42:01,740
Dominic Kearney's father
beat Dominic senseless

602
00:42:01,770 --> 00:42:02,990
with a kettle Saturday,

603
00:42:03,160 --> 00:42:05,093
and is staying with me
and me sister, Dominic is.

604
00:42:05,120 --> 00:42:06,746
So, at least his father'll
take a bit of a break

605
00:42:06,770 --> 00:42:08,086
from his beatin' of him.

606
00:42:08,690 --> 00:42:10,510
And him, a policeman.

607
00:42:10,690 --> 00:42:12,650
Isn't that news?

608
00:42:12,820 --> 00:42:15,080
Ar, that Dominic's
an awful little bollocks.

609
00:42:15,390 --> 00:42:16,480
That's no news.

610
00:42:16,650 --> 00:42:18,910
Still, he was in a bad way
when I came upon him.

611
00:42:19,090 --> 00:42:21,293
I'd beat him with a kettle
meself if I wasn't old.

612
00:42:21,310 --> 00:42:23,570
It's news is all I'm sayin'.

613
00:42:23,750 --> 00:42:25,920
That's no news.
That's shite news.

614
00:42:26,100 --> 00:42:28,366
Okay, so, Mrs. O'Riordan, thanks for the...

615
00:42:28,660 --> 00:42:29,970
I'll see ya when I see ya.

616
00:42:52,170 --> 00:42:53,846
And you can tell that skitter of a son of mine

617
00:42:53,860 --> 00:42:55,650
he'd better be home by teatime,

618
00:42:55,680 --> 00:42:57,666
or it's over to batter
the both of ye I'll be,

619
00:42:57,690 --> 00:43:00,346
and your dreary fecking sister, too!

620
00:43:09,920 --> 00:43:11,310
Oh, hello there, Colm.

621
00:43:11,400 --> 00:43:13,993
Will I see you at Jonjo's tonight
for that pint you owe me?

622
00:43:14,010 --> 00:43:15,010
I owe you no pin...

623
00:43:16,190 --> 00:43:17,053
You will, Peadar.

624
00:43:17,060 --> 00:43:18,370
Good man yourself.

625
00:44:30,220 --> 00:44:31,440
Whoa, stand.

626
00:44:32,180 --> 00:44:33,180
Stand.

627
00:46:12,280 --> 00:46:13,320
What's that, Jenny?

628
00:46:15,980 --> 00:46:17,920
Will we go to the pub for ourselves?

629
00:46:19,150 --> 00:46:20,370
We will. Come on.

630
00:46:38,090 --> 00:46:40,326
One drink you're havin', lady,
then it's off home with ya.

631
00:46:40,350 --> 00:46:43,220
I've a shirt that wants
ironing for the morning.

632
00:46:44,090 --> 00:46:46,010
Okay, Daddy.

633
00:46:46,180 --> 00:46:49,660
Aye. Off to the mainland
in the morning I'm headin'.

634
00:46:49,813 --> 00:46:52,146
That's why I need the clean shirt, like.

635
00:46:53,490 --> 00:46:55,986
"And why are you off to the mainland
in the mornin', Peadar?"

636
00:46:56,020 --> 00:46:58,450
Oh, thanks for asking, Colm.
I'll tell ya why.

637
00:46:58,630 --> 00:47:00,133
They've asked for extra manpower

638
00:47:00,150 --> 00:47:01,980
for a couple of the executions

639
00:47:02,150 --> 00:47:04,330
in case there's any kind of a to-do, like.

640
00:47:04,500 --> 00:47:06,810
Six bob and a free lunch they're payin' me.

641
00:47:06,980 --> 00:47:09,250
And sure I'd have gone for nothin'.

642
00:47:09,420 --> 00:47:11,973
I've always wanted to see an execution,
haven't you?

643
00:47:11,990 --> 00:47:13,886
Although, I'd have preferred a hanging.

644
00:47:13,900 --> 00:47:15,560
Who are they executin'?

645
00:47:15,730 --> 00:47:19,313
The Free State lads are executin'
a couple of the IRA lads.

646
00:47:20,130 --> 00:47:22,100
Or is it the other way around?

647
00:47:23,310 --> 00:47:26,260
I find it hard to follow these days.

648
00:47:26,340 --> 00:47:28,293
Wasn't it so much easier when we
was all on the same side,

649
00:47:28,310 --> 00:47:30,413
and it was just the English we was killin'?

650
00:47:30,440 --> 00:47:33,100
I think it was.
I preferred it.

651
00:47:33,270 --> 00:47:35,190
But you don't care who's executin' who?

652
00:47:35,360 --> 00:47:37,750
For six bob and a free lunch,
I don't care!

653
00:47:38,060 --> 00:47:40,240
They could be executin' you.

654
00:47:40,670 --> 00:47:42,110
Why don't you come with me?

655
00:47:42,280 --> 00:47:45,486
You could write a miserable
feckin' song about it.

656
00:47:47,550 --> 00:47:49,110
Nah, I'm only messin'.

657
00:48:14,360 --> 00:48:15,790
Who are them?

658
00:48:15,913 --> 00:48:19,033
Music students, I think, from Lisdoonvarna.

659
00:48:30,240 --> 00:48:33,030
Another whisky, anyways, Jonjo.

660
00:48:33,100 --> 00:48:35,913
Jeez, you're goin' at it at a
fair old lick tonight, Padraic.

661
00:48:35,940 --> 00:48:37,900
Yeah? What's it to ya?

662
00:49:09,150 --> 00:49:10,240
Padraic, don't now...

663
00:49:14,330 --> 00:49:16,413
Go get Siobhan, Dominic, would ya?

664
00:49:20,120 --> 00:49:21,633
What are you after, gobshite?

665
00:49:21,640 --> 00:49:23,290
Another beatin', is it?

666
00:49:23,340 --> 00:49:24,606
You, copper, I'm allowed
to chat to you, aren't I?

667
00:49:25,600 --> 00:49:27,726
It's just tubbyguts
I'm not allowed to talk to.

668
00:49:27,730 --> 00:49:30,400
Actually, no, I'd rather
you didn't talk to me neither.

669
00:49:30,480 --> 00:49:32,610
Oh, well, anyways,

670
00:49:32,780 --> 00:49:35,000
do you want to know what the
three things that I hate the most

671
00:49:35,050 --> 00:49:36,733
on Inisherin is? Not really.

672
00:49:36,766 --> 00:49:37,720
One,

673
00:49:38,440 --> 00:49:39,440
policemen.

674
00:49:40,400 --> 00:49:41,970
Two,

675
00:49:42,140 --> 00:49:44,006
pudgy fiddle players.

676
00:49:44,450 --> 00:49:46,400
And three...

677
00:49:46,580 --> 00:49:48,813
Wait, I had some funny thing
for three. What was it?

678
00:49:48,840 --> 00:49:51,280
Uh, I'll start again. One, um,

679
00:49:51,450 --> 00:49:52,760
policemen.

680
00:49:52,930 --> 00:49:53,890
Two...

681
00:49:55,540 --> 00:49:56,890
Pudgy fiddle players.

682
00:49:57,070 --> 00:49:59,160
Pudgy fiddle players.

683
00:49:59,330 --> 00:50:01,070
And shite, what was three?

684
00:50:01,100 --> 00:50:02,940
Go on back to your own gang now, Padraic.
I'm serious, now.

685
00:50:02,990 --> 00:50:03,770
Serious, are ya?

686
00:50:06,560 --> 00:50:08,640
And talkin' to me, are ya?

687
00:50:11,040 --> 00:50:11,780
Siobhan!

688
00:50:14,870 --> 00:50:17,073
Padraic's out of his brains
on whisky, and Colm's there.

689
00:50:17,090 --> 00:50:18,220
You'd better come.

690
00:50:25,570 --> 00:50:28,140
You, Colm Doherty, do you know
what you used to be?

691
00:50:28,320 --> 00:50:30,140
No, Padraic, what did I used to be?

692
00:50:30,320 --> 00:50:31,100
Nice!

693
00:50:32,150 --> 00:50:33,450
You used to be nice!

694
00:50:34,320 --> 00:50:36,110
Didn't he not?

695
00:50:36,280 --> 00:50:38,070
And now, do you know what you are?

696
00:50:38,540 --> 00:50:39,810
Not nice.

697
00:50:39,980 --> 00:50:42,160
Ah, well,

698
00:50:42,330 --> 00:50:45,680
I suppose niceness doesn't last then,
does it, Padraic?

699
00:50:45,860 --> 00:50:47,510
But will I tell ya something that does last?

700
00:50:47,680 --> 00:50:50,250
What? And don't say
somethin' stupid like music.

701
00:50:50,430 --> 00:50:52,430
Music lasts.Knew it!

702
00:50:52,600 --> 00:50:55,390
And paintings last.
And poetry lasts.

703
00:50:55,560 --> 00:50:57,130
So does niceness.

704
00:51:00,480 --> 00:51:01,610
Do you know who we remember

705
00:51:01,780 --> 00:51:03,920
for how nice they was
in the 17th century?

706
00:51:04,090 --> 00:51:06,310
Who? Absolutely no one.

707
00:51:06,480 --> 00:51:09,440
Yet we all remember the music of the time.

708
00:51:09,620 --> 00:51:11,580
Everyone, to a man, knows Mozart's name.

709
00:51:12,053 --> 00:51:14,520
Well, I don't, so there goes that theory.

710
00:51:15,106 --> 00:51:17,800
And anyway, we're talkin' about niceness.

711
00:51:18,060 --> 00:51:19,150
Not whatsisname.

712
00:51:20,630 --> 00:51:22,590
My mammy, she was nice.

713
00:51:23,500 --> 00:51:26,160
I remember her.

714
00:51:26,330 --> 00:51:28,380
And my daddy, he was nice.
I remember him.

715
00:51:28,550 --> 00:51:31,250
And my sister, she's nice.

716
00:51:31,420 --> 00:51:34,690
I'll remember her.
Forever I'll remember her.

717
00:51:34,860 --> 00:51:37,120
And who else will?
PADRAIC: "Who else will" what?

718
00:51:37,300 --> 00:51:39,340
Remember Siobhan and your niceness?

719
00:51:40,520 --> 00:51:41,220
No one will.

720
00:51:42,130 --> 00:51:43,130
In 50 years' time,

721
00:51:43,300 --> 00:51:45,180
no one will remember any of us.

722
00:51:47,570 --> 00:51:50,050
Yet the music of a man
who lived two centuries ago...

723
00:51:50,220 --> 00:51:51,970
"Yet," he says, like he's English.

724
00:51:53,400 --> 00:51:54,530
Come home, Padraic.

725
00:51:54,710 --> 00:51:57,710
I don't give a feck about Mozart,

726
00:51:58,320 --> 00:51:59,970
or Borvoven,

727
00:52:00,150 --> 00:52:03,280
or any of them funny name feckers.

728
00:52:03,450 --> 00:52:04,890
I'm Padraic Suilleabhain.

729
00:52:07,280 --> 00:52:09,070
And I'm nice.

730
00:52:09,240 --> 00:52:10,770
Come home.

731
00:52:10,940 --> 00:52:13,873
So you'd rather be friends
with this fella, would ya?

732
00:52:14,093 --> 00:52:15,340
A fella who

733
00:52:15,400 --> 00:52:16,990
beats his own son
black and blue every night

734
00:52:17,106 --> 00:52:19,046
that he's not fiddling with him.

735
00:52:19,690 --> 00:52:22,640
I never told him that, Daddy.
He's... He's just drunk now.

736
00:52:23,130 --> 00:52:24,520
You used to be nice.

737
00:52:26,220 --> 00:52:27,570
Or did you never used to be?

738
00:52:30,390 --> 00:52:31,610
Oh, God.

739
00:52:34,790 --> 00:52:36,530
Maybe you never used to be.

740
00:52:53,330 --> 00:52:55,030
I'll have a word with him, Colm.

741
00:52:55,330 --> 00:52:57,340
You don't need to do anything drastic.

742
00:52:57,380 --> 00:52:59,030
He won't be botherin' you no more.

743
00:52:59,210 --> 00:53:00,210
That's a shame.

744
00:53:01,770 --> 00:53:03,520
That's the most interesting he's ever been.

745
00:53:03,560 --> 00:53:05,820
I think I like him again now.

746
00:53:08,560 --> 00:53:12,090
It was the 18th century, anyway. Mozart.

747
00:53:12,740 --> 00:53:13,960
Not the 17th.

748
00:53:50,040 --> 00:53:52,830
Siobhan Suilleabhain!
Well, well.

749
00:53:53,000 --> 00:53:54,886
I only came in for rashers, Mrs. O'Riordan.

750
00:53:54,910 --> 00:53:56,050
I've no time to talk, I'm afraid.

751
00:53:56,220 --> 00:53:57,310
Letter came for ya.

752
00:54:00,830 --> 00:54:02,310
Fell open, did it?

753
00:54:02,490 --> 00:54:04,766
Aye, in the heat, I suppose.

754
00:54:10,490 --> 00:54:11,500
A job offer, is it?

755
00:54:18,630 --> 00:54:22,720
A job offer from a library
on the mainland, is it?

756
00:54:22,900 --> 00:54:26,160
Just the rashers, please, Mrs. O'Riordan.
About ten of them.

757
00:54:34,610 --> 00:54:36,300
You never tell me anything!

758
00:54:39,090 --> 00:54:40,520
Well, it'd crucify him, your leaving!

759
00:54:40,700 --> 00:54:42,220
Hey, no one's leaving!

760
00:54:57,590 --> 00:54:59,410
Listen, I didn't come down to chat.

761
00:54:59,590 --> 00:55:01,173
I just came down to say
that all that last night

762
00:55:01,200 --> 00:55:02,590
was just the whisky talkin', Colm.

763
00:55:02,760 --> 00:55:03,770
All what last night?

764
00:55:03,940 --> 00:55:05,900
All whatever it was I was sayin'.

765
00:55:06,070 --> 00:55:07,180
What were you sayin'?

766
00:55:07,200 --> 00:55:10,160
Uh... Yeah.
I can't remember much of it,

767
00:55:10,470 --> 00:55:12,786
but I remember the gist
of it wasn't the best.

768
00:55:12,820 --> 00:55:14,250
You always know, don't ya?

769
00:55:17,950 --> 00:55:20,700
